Sure! Here's an example of a simple game in Mojolicious that uses the Mojo::UserAgent and Mojo::DOM modules to fetch and parse URLs:
```
use Mojolicious::Lite;
use Mojo::UserAgent;
use Mojo::DOM;
# Define routes
get '/' => sub {
  my $c = shift;
  my $ua = Mojo::UserAgent->new;
  my $dom = Mojo::DOM->new;
  # Fetch and parse URL
  my $url = $c->req->url->to_abs;
  my $content = $ua->get($url)->content;
  $dom->load($content);
  # Parse page HTML
  my $parser = Mojo::DOM->new($content);
  my @links = $parser->find('a[href]')->map(sub {
    my $link = Mojo::DOM->new($_[0]);
    my $href = $link->attr('href');
    return ($href);
  });
  # Render page content
  $c->render(text => \@links);
};
# Start server
app->start;
```
This code fetches a URL, parses the HTML content and finds all links. The links are then rendered as links in the HTML. Note that you'll need to have Mojolicious installed and configured in order to run this code.

Sure, here's an example of a simple game implemented in JavaScript that executes in a browser and plays a sound when the "worm" touches the wall:
```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Worm Game</title>
    <script>
      function drawWorm() {
        // Draw worm on canvas
        var ctx = document.getElementById("canvas").getContext("2d");
        ctx.fillStyle = "rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.5)";
        ctx.fillRect(0, 0, 50, 50);
        // Play sound when worm touches wall
        var audio = new Audio("worm-sound.mp3");
        audio.play();
      }
      // Draw worm on canvas
      function drawWormOnCanvas() {
        var ctx = document.getElementById("canvas").getContext("2d");
        ctx.fillStyle = "rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5)";
        ctx.fillRect(0, 0, 50, 50);
      }
      // Handle click event on canvas
      var canvas = document.getElementById("canvas");
      canvas.addEventListener("click", function(event) {
        drawWorm();
        drawWormOnCanvas();
      });
    </script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <canvas id="canvas" width="400" height="400"></canvas>
    <script>
      // Start game loop
      setInterval(drawWorm, 100);
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```
This code creates a simple canvas element and an audio element. When the page loads, the canvas is drawn with a funny worm (using a simple image) and a click handler is registered for the canvas. When the worm touches the wall, the audio element is played. You can replace the sound file with any other audio file of your choice.
You can also add more features to the game, such as changing the speed of the worm, or adding a score that increases when the worm reaches the wall.
